---
description: Next.js / React frontend conventions for a professional, accurate, accessible UI
globs: ["frontend/**/*.tsx", "frontend/**/*.ts"]
---

# Data fetching
- TanStack Query for all server state. No manual `useState` + `useEffect` fetch chains.
- Every view that fetches data explicitly handles three states: loading, error, and empty. A blank
  screen, an uncaught promise rejection, or a silently-empty list with no explanation is not acceptable.
- After a mutation that changes server state (file an appeal, resolve an appeal, override a verdict,
  change policy), invalidate the relevant query so the UI reflects the new state without a manual
  refresh — this is the actual implementation of PROJECT_PLAN.md's "reflects real system state" goal.

# Components
- Server components by default. Add `'use client'` only where interactivity or hooks are actually
  needed — don't default every component to client-side.
- Role-based access (`(user)` vs `(admin)` route groups) is enforced in middleware with a redirect, not
  by rendering a page and conditionally hiding parts of it client-side.

# Forms
- Validate with a schema (zod) that mirrors the backend DTO shape, so a user sees a validation error
  before the request round-trips to the API.
- Disable the submit control during a pending mutation. Show a clear success or failure state after —
  don't leave the user wondering whether a click did anything.

# Accessibility, not as an afterthought
- Every form input has an associated label.
- Every submitted image has meaningful alt text.
- Outcome status (Approved/Flagged/Blocked) is never communicated by color alone — pair it with text
  or an icon so it's legible without color perception.

# Types
- Import the shared outcome/category/enforcement constants from the same source the backend uses
  (or a generated/shared types package) rather than re-declaring matching string literals on the
  frontend. Two independently-typed copies of the same enum are how they drift apart.
